00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:02,640
- This is a camera that can see sound.

2
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:05,970
In other words, it can show
you where in a scene sounds

3
00:00:05,970 --> 00:00:06,803
are coming from.

4
00:00:06,803 --> 00:00:08,370
How acoustic cameras work,

5
00:00:08,370 --> 00:00:10,980
and what they're capable of is remarkable.

6
00:00:10,980 --> 00:00:14,640
But before we get into that,
I went to an anechoic chamber

7
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:16,320
to have a play with one.

8
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:19,890
Here's me playing the ukulele
and talking at the same time.

9
00:00:19,890 --> 00:00:22,230
It's interesting that the
sound appears to switch

10
00:00:22,230 --> 00:00:25,440
between coming from my mouth
and coming from the ukulele,

11
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:27,930
even though sometimes
both are making a sound

12
00:00:27,930 --> 00:00:28,950
at the same time.

13
00:00:28,950 --> 00:00:31,380
And brilliantly, this
is completely analogous

14
00:00:31,380 --> 00:00:34,140
to a traditional light-based camera.

15
00:00:34,140 --> 00:00:37,500
What we have here is an
issue of dynamic range.

16
00:00:37,500 --> 00:00:40,770
If you have your camera
set to automatic exposure

17
00:00:40,770 --> 00:00:42,990
which your smartphone is by default,

18
00:00:42,990 --> 00:00:45,630
and you shoot a video of a dim light,

19
00:00:45,630 --> 00:00:49,290
then turn on a much brighter
light, the camera will switch

20
00:00:49,290 --> 00:00:52,440
between showing you lots
of detail of the dim light

21
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:55,530
to showing you lots of
detail of the bright light.

22
00:00:55,530 --> 00:00:58,650
And the same thing is happening
here with the ukulele.

23
00:00:58,650 --> 00:01:01,440
The ukulele is louder than my voice.

24
00:01:01,440 --> 00:01:03,180
So when the ukulele is being played,

25
00:01:03,180 --> 00:01:06,750
the acoustic camera dials
down its sensitivity

26
00:01:06,750 --> 00:01:09,870
and you can no longer see my voice.

27
00:01:09,870 --> 00:01:12,390
But when I stop strumming the ukulele, the camera dials up the sensitivity, and then you can see my voice.


28
00:01:12,390 --> 00:01:15,300


29
00:01:15,300 --> 00:01:18,150
What's really cool is
that because my voice is

30
00:01:18,150 --> 00:01:20,730
in a different frequency
range to the ukulele,

31
00:01:20,730 --> 00:01:23,370
it's possible to isolate just my voice

32
00:01:23,370 --> 00:01:26,040
and ignore the ukulele or vice versa.

33
00:01:26,040 --> 00:01:27,810
And actually, this starts to hint

34
00:01:27,810 --> 00:01:31,710
at one of the industrial
applications for acoustic cameras.

35
00:01:31,710 --> 00:01:34,768
One really noisy appliance
is a vacuum cleaner.

36
00:01:34,768 --> 00:01:36,990
(vacuum cleaner buzzing)

37
00:01:36,990 --> 00:01:39,420
It just seems like a cacophony of sound.

38
00:01:39,420 --> 00:01:41,190
But look at this spectrogram,

39
00:01:41,190 --> 00:01:44,460
which is like a heat map of
the different frequencies

40
00:01:44,460 --> 00:01:46,260
that the vacuum cleaner is producing.

41
00:01:46,260 --> 00:01:47,910
You can see that there are a handful

42
00:01:47,910 --> 00:01:50,190
of really strong frequencies.

43
00:01:50,190 --> 00:01:51,450
With the acoustic camera software,

44
00:01:51,450 --> 00:01:53,670
you can isolate different frequencies.

45
00:01:53,670 --> 00:01:57,060
So look, this frequency
here we now can see

46
00:01:57,060 --> 00:01:59,670
is from the tube of the vacuum cleaner.

47
00:01:59,670 --> 00:02:02,130
So we now know that the tube
of the vacuum cleaner resonates

48
00:02:02,130 --> 00:02:05,100
at 400 hertz, and we
can see that the motor

49
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:09,210
of the vacuum cleaner produces
a frequency of 7,000 hertz.

50
00:02:09,210 --> 00:02:10,830
And all this is really useful information

51
00:02:10,830 --> 00:02:13,800
if you're trying to engineer
a quieter appliance.

52
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:16,380
Another cool trick is once you have the recording, you can use something akin to the eyedropper tool in Photoshop to point at different parts of the recording and see what just that part sounds like.

