110
00:04:50,580 --> 00:04:52,110
in super-slow motion.

111
00:04:52,110 --> 00:04:53,400
Before we get to that though,

112
00:04:53,400 --> 00:04:56,280
I want to explain how
acoustic cameras work.

113
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:58,500
And actually this relates to
a video I made a while back

114
00:04:58,500 --> 00:05:01,560
about how humans detect
where sounds are coming from,

115
00:05:01,560 --> 00:05:03,030
linked to that in the
card in the description,

116
00:05:03,030 --> 00:05:06,030
but here's a quick summary
of the salient part.

117
00:05:06,030 --> 00:05:07,830
We detect where sounds
are coming from based

118
00:05:07,830 --> 00:05:10,980
on the timings of sound
reaching our two ears.

119
00:05:10,980 --> 00:05:13,110
So if a sound is coming
from directly in front,

120
00:05:13,110 --> 00:05:14,970
it'll reach both ears at the same time.

121
00:05:14,970 --> 00:05:17,520
And that's how we know
it's coming from in front.

122
00:05:17,520 --> 00:05:20,700
But suppose there's a
delay of 0.3 milliseconds,

123
00:05:20,700 --> 00:05:22,770
that tells our brain the sound is coming

124
00:05:22,770 --> 00:05:25,680
from like off to one
side, like over there.

125
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:26,790
But actually it could also be coming

126
00:05:26,790 --> 00:05:27,810
from over there, couldn't it?

127
00:05:27,810 --> 00:05:28,950
Cuz the delay would be the same,

128
00:05:28,950 --> 00:05:31,680
or like up there at an
angle, or down there.

129
00:05:31,680 --> 00:05:34,200
In fact, there's a whole
region of possible places

130
00:05:34,200 --> 00:05:35,580
the sound could be coming from.

131
00:05:35,580 --> 00:05:38,550
And that region is called
the cone of confusion,

132
00:05:38,550 --> 00:05:42,210
though technically it's a
hyperboloid of confusion.

133
00:05:42,210 --> 00:05:43,530
Here's an illustration of that.

134
00:05:43,530 --> 00:05:45,450
The two yellow dots are the ears

135
00:05:45,450 --> 00:05:48,810
and here is the cone of
possible locations of a sound

136
00:05:48,810 --> 00:05:51,900
for which the delay between
the two ears is the same.

137
00:05:51,900 --> 00:05:54,060
So how do you reduce that surface

138
00:05:54,060 --> 00:05:57,120
of possible sound locations
down to a single point?

139
00:05:57,120 --> 00:06:00,330
Well, the human brain has lots
of clever ways of doing that.

140
00:06:00,330 --> 00:06:02,340
But for a device like an acoustic camera,

141
00:06:02,340 --> 00:06:04,680
you just need to add more ears.

142
00:06:04,680 --> 00:06:08,310
Like here, look, imagine
if I added a third ear.

143
00:06:08,310 --> 00:06:11,760
Well, the same sound source
will create a new cone

144
00:06:11,760 --> 00:06:15,060
based on the delay
between this pair of ears.

145
00:06:15,060 --> 00:06:17,220
So now we know that the
sound must be coming

146
00:06:17,220 --> 00:06:20,760
from a point that rests
on both of these cones.

147
00:06:20,760 --> 00:06:23,940
In other words, somewhere
along this intersecting line.

148
00:06:23,940 --> 00:06:26,670
You might be thinking, well
there's another pairing of ears

149
00:06:26,670 --> 00:06:27,720
we haven't looked at.

150
00:06:27,720 --> 00:06:29,970
These two ears make another cone.

151
00:06:29,970 --> 00:06:31,890
But actually the way the maths works out

152
00:06:31,890 --> 00:06:35,010
all three cones intersect
at the same hyperbole.

153
00:06:35,010 --> 00:06:37,980
So to really pinpoint
the location of a sound,

154
00:06:37,980 --> 00:06:39,330
you need a fourth ear.

155
00:06:39,330 --> 00:06:42,720
A fourth ear would give us three new ear pairings and therefore three new cones of confusion.

156
00:06:42,720 --> 00:06:46,020


157
00:06:46,020 --> 00:06:48,120
But if I showed all three new cones,

158
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:50,490
that would be confusing.

159
00:06:50,490 --> 00:06:52,500
But just by adding one of them, we can see

160
00:06:52,500 --> 00:06:56,280
that it passes through the
hyperbole in just one place.

161
00:06:56,280 --> 00:06:57,510
So with four ears,

162
00:06:57,510 --> 00:07:00,570
you should be able to
locate the exact direction

163
00:07:00,570 --> 00:07:02,850
and distance to the sound source.

164
00:07:02,850 --> 00:07:06,120
So why do these acoustic cameras
need more than four ears?

165
00:07:06,120 --> 00:07:09,810
Well, what if there were two
sound sources simultaneously?

166
00:07:09,810 --> 00:07:10,860
In that scenario,

167
00:07:10,860 --> 00:07:15,120
two microphones would receive
completely different sounds.

168
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:17,595
That's because the sounds
from the two sources

169
00:07:17,595 --> 00:07:19,500
would overlap differently

170
00:07:19,500 --> 00:07:21,336
because of the different travel times

171
00:07:21,336 --> 00:07:23,820
to the two different microphones.

172
00:07:23,820 --> 00:07:26,220
That's okay for humans
because humans are good

173
00:07:26,220 --> 00:07:30,000
at filtering sounds in
all sorts of clever ways.

174
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,250
But for software, that's a problem.

175
00:07:32,250 --> 00:07:35,610
So instead, what the
software does is analyze

176
00:07:35,610 --> 00:07:39,120
individual frequencies
instead of the whole waveform.

177
00:07:39,120 --> 00:07:41,460
So where a human brain
is trying to match up

178
00:07:41,460 --> 00:07:45,660
complex wave forms, the
acoustic camera is looking at

179
00:07:45,660 --> 00:07:48,521
individual frequencies and
the difference in phase

180
00:07:48,521 --> 00:07:50,370
at the two microphones.

181
00:07:50,370 --> 00:07:51,660
And it turns out that when you're looking

182
00:07:51,660 --> 00:07:53,730
at different frequencies individually,

183
00:07:53,730 --> 00:07:57,510
the distance between mics
becomes really important.

184
00:07:57,510 --> 00:07:58,860
For any given frequency,

185
00:07:58,860 --> 00:08:01,110
there's an optimum distance between mics.

186
00:08:01,110 --> 00:08:04,260
So by having lots of
mics, you can have a range

187
00:08:04,260 --> 00:08:06,900
of different distances between mics,

188
00:08:06,900 --> 00:08:08,340
and so you'll be able to analyze

189
00:08:08,340 --> 00:08:10,830
more frequencies more accurately.

190
00:08:10,830 --> 00:08:13,020
In my previous video
that I mentioned earlier,

191
00:08:13,020 --> 00:08:17,220
I talk about why a high
frequency sound is problematic

192
00:08:17,220 --> 00:08:19,650
for microphones that are far apart

193
00:08:19,650 --> 00:08:23,430
and actually it's problematic
for human ears as well.

194
00:08:23,430 --> 00:08:24,630
So I won't repeat myself,

195
00:08:24,630 --> 00:08:26,310
but the link is in the description.

196
00:08:26,310 --> 00:08:30,390
But anyway, all this explains
why this acoustic camera also

197
00:08:30,390 --> 00:08:34,559
from gfai tech has mics
that are irregularly spaced.

198
00:08:34,559 --> 00:08:36,389
If the mics replaced at regular intervals,

199
00:08:36,390 --> 00:08:38,880
you would have some repeating distances

200
00:08:38,880 --> 00:08:40,049
between pairs of mics.

201
00:08:40,049 --> 00:08:41,939
Like all these distances are the same,

202
00:08:41,940 --> 00:08:43,409
all these distances are the same.

203
00:08:43,409 --> 00:08:45,300
By having a irregularly spaced mics,

204
00:08:45,300 --> 00:08:48,690
you cover a greater range
of distances between mics.

205
00:08:48,690 --> 00:08:51,000
How acoustic cameras
work is more complicated

206
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:52,470
than I've presented here.

207
00:08:52,470 --> 00:08:53,400
Like for example,

208
00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:57,007
having more mics gives you
essentially better resolution,

209
00:08:57,007 --> 00:08:59,850
but it's beyond the scope of this video.

210
00:08:59,850 --> 00:09:01,260
I kind of glossed over the fact

211
00:09:01,260 --> 00:09:04,860
that you get depth information
from an array of microphones.

212
00:09:04,860 --> 00:09:06,630
So here's a more recent model

213
00:09:06,630 --> 00:09:09,630
from gfai tech that
takes advantage of that.

214
00:09:09,630 --> 00:09:11,550
The video camera in the middle of this one

215
00:09:11,550 --> 00:09:13,020
captures depth information.

216
00:09:13,020 --> 00:09:14,820
So when you're traveling around an object,

217
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:16,380
you're basically scanning it.

218
00:09:16,380 --> 00:09:19,800
You can then map the
sound onto that 3D object

219
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:21,000
and look around it.

220
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:21,833
How cool is that?

221
00:09:21,833 --> 00:09:22,800
But the coolest thing for me

222
